metadata.name: Special Token [RESERVE PASS] #17
metadata.description:
Back when I was a researcher at a human-computer interaction lab, I parked in the adjacent neighborhood and rode the city bus into campus.

Usually this was a pretty uneventful affair.

One spring day though, the bus was packed and I had to stand right up front by the driver. Despite trying to appear busy enough not to be bothered, the driver struck up a conversation.

At some point in the short trip, we stopped at a red light. It was then that he made an off-hand comment that I've remembered ever since.

‚ÄúThe moment between when the light turns green and when I realize it, that‚Äôs where my soul resides.‚Äù

I‚Äôm not sure how you‚Äôre supposed to respond to that. But nevertheless it smacked me.

So: do not consider each of these my personal signature as an artist, developer, and tinkerer.

Do consider them an expended shard of my soul and the culmination of experiences that have led up to this moment.

This is the light turning green.

---

THIS TOKEN IS A RESERVE PASS (it‚Äôs ‚ú®special‚ú®)

- This token will function as a reserve pass for any future drop on fx(hash) that has a total edition size of > 100 (ie, most of my drops, other than dedicated ‚Äúsketch‚Äù projects that may have intentionally fewer editions)

- Future reserves will be limited to holders of this token, and holding this token will guarantee you a dedicated 24 hour reserve spot on such projects.

- Holding any token from my prior projects will make you eligible to mint from this drop (I will take a final snapshot ~1 hr prior to drop).

- I have created an edition size of 60, but only 40 will be open for minting at this time. I‚Äôll reserve the remainder for issuing or burning at my discretion.

- I will also airdrop ~9 editions to the top collectors of my previous projects (consider Twitter to be the source of info on this prior to the drop)

WHY?

I don‚Äôt like the idea of picking and choosing who gets a reserve and who doesn‚Äôt.

I love you all üôè

metadata.name: Step by Step #26
metadata.description:
Step by Step explores the feeling of being stuck, confined - walking the path ahead of you often only seeing the immediate next step until exhaustion. We all feel this way from time to time ‚Äî in our lives, jobs, bodies, situations ‚Äî yet in our search for something, we shouldn't forget that there can still be beauty along the path.

The project takes some inspiration from Henri Matisse, both in the aesthetics of his later works (i.e. the "Cut Outs") and metaphorically in the sense that he had underwent medical treatment which left him wheelchair- or bed-bound towards the later part of his life, forcing him to give up painting, yet in his exploration of this new creative medium which involved cutting paper and pinning them up, his unorthodox work went on to become the most transformative of his career.

Released as part of the 4th edition of the Cure¬≥ Parkinson's cure fundraiser exhibition organized by Artwise Curators and Bonhams as part of a specially comissioned selection of generative artists minting NFTs, curated by Foteini Valeonti and Alex Estorick with the support of fx(hash) at Bonhams, London from 13-17th January 2023.

metadata.name: #2023Streams #61
metadata.description:
#2023Streams is a color theory study that explores the use of algorithmically-generated color palettes and the juxtaposition of color harmonies keyed on a common hue. It brings playfulness to experimentation through the use of randomized features that control lighting, color assortment, and more, to create interesting, vibrant compositions.

I consider this piece‚Äîmy generative "genesis"‚Äîto be a preliminary "sketch" whose desired outcomes are insights into color and light that might be applied to more advanced projects in the future.

This piece is also a first step for me, into the world of professional art. An art school dropout and software engineer by profession, I've been hacking on generative art projects, games, and interactive experiences for more than two decades. But now, in 2023, it's my time to focus and prioritize art and creativity.

Each image can be modified using the following keyboard commands:
- [d] Download the rendered image
- [j] Toggle between "jungle" (dimensional) and "jazz" (flat) modes
- [l] Toggle between light and dark backgrounds
- [e] Toggle between curved (ellipse) and flat (rectangle) shapes
- [s] Enable/disable shadows and highlights
- [t] Enable/disable transparency

Each image is rendered at 2400 x 2400 pixels by default. This should be suitable for an 8" x 8" output (at 300 dpi). Should you desire a higher resolution output, the image can be magnified up to 6x by clicking the "open ‚ÜóÔ∏è" link and appending a density parameter to the URL, e.g. `&density=4` 

Lastly, #2023Streams is licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International license. This license allows reusers to distribute, remix, adapt, and build upon the material in any medium or format, so long as attribution is given to the creator. The license allows for commercial use.

What does this license mean? It means I invite you to have fun with your new piece, get creative and bring something new into the world.

I hope you enjoy these outputs as much as I do. Thank you for stopping by‚Äîand hopefully collecting.

metadata.name: A Pile, To Be Sorted #22
metadata.description:
Compartmentalization in service of clarity.
Dedicated to my Dad and, by extension, his advice.

When I get overwhelmed (which is often), I typically call my dad. He‚Äôs always got some relatable story from his life I‚Äôve never heard before, OR he hits me with the same piece of advice he‚Äôs been giving me for as long as I can remember:

‚ÄúOf course it‚Äôs hard to stay calm when you look at the pile in front of you. Every responsibility, want and obligation, is not something we‚Äôre meant to face all at once. Break it up, take on one task from the pile, and focus on that.‚Äù

This has been such a stable pattern that I often don‚Äôt need to hear him say it. I‚Äôll finish describing what‚Äôs going on and stop him before he can even start, so he doesn‚Äôt have to waste his breath on something I should know by now, it‚Äôs already helping just to remember it.

The best thing I can do for myself is to pick something out of the pile and handle it in isolation. I find that often each task will grow the pile exponentially. It‚Äôs easy to handle my health and fitness when that‚Äôs all I have to think about. But then I have to think about finances, maintaining friendships, taking care of my plants, dating, and finding time for a hobby. Each one of those things has its own nuances and complications. With all that in mind, going to the gym sounds overwhelming.

But‚Äî Going to the gym is easy. Pick one thing, focus, get it done, and watch the pile shrink. Repeat.

I‚Äôve opted to create a design which illustrates this overwhelm and demonstrates how quickly those individual tasks lose form in the pile.

Press 's' to save a .png
Press '1', '2', or '3' to change render size
Press 't' to toggle linen texture (for use printing onto textured paper or cloth)

Created by Chris McCully in October 2023 using p5.js, chroma.js, and GLSL

metadata.name: Garden, Monoliths #14
metadata.description:
"Garden, Monoliths" is the result of an algorithm that started in April 2021. It was called "Grass.js".
Spring was blooming all around the house, taking over the stones and remnants of ancient battles that stood here. Inspiration was everywhere.
The initial goal was to use mathematical formulas for creating patterns inspired by the density of nature, that could be used by a pen plotter, so it kept focusing on outputting vector lines. This history and practice produced a graphical style based on line strokes, plus occasionally some transparent, filled shapes.
Each artwork will be either "Garden" or "Monolith", for they are variations of two existing designs from the workshop.

metadata.name: The Pure Zone #42
metadata.description:
"The Pure Zone" is a captivating and visually stunning form of artistic expression. 
It is characterized by its use of clean lines, minimalistic designs, and a focus on creating a sense of purity and tranquility.
I employed a limited color palette, consisting mainly of neutral tones such as whites, grays, and pastels. This deliberate choice enhances the overall sense of calm and simplicity in the artwork.
The subject in "The Pure Zone" is abstract representations of emotions or concepts. The aim is to evoke a feeling of serenity and inner peace through this artwork.
One notable feature of "The Pure Zone" is its meticulous attention to detail. Each line and stroke is purposefully placed to create a harmonious composition that draws the viewer's eye into the artwork. This attention to detail adds depth and dimension to the piece while maintaining its overall minimalist aesthetic.

"The Pure Zone" serves as a visual reminder to find beauty in simplicity and embrace moments of stillness in our busy lives.
